recordings.loc: Arcata, Humboldt County, California
recordings.rmk:
This 1 minutes and 36 second recording documents approximately 45 alarm calls from a single adult unsexed Cedar Waxwing. This waxwing had just flown in and saw me and looped around to land at the top of a Red Alder. I suspect that there is a nest site nearby as I have heard a distressed waxwing nearby recently. There is one call type exhibited from the focal individual: a whistled falling ‚Äòsee‚Äô similar to several species of thrush alarm notes. However there is a point in this recording when a unassociated flock of three Cedar Waxwings flew over the very tree that the focal waxwing is perched in.

More details of the context of this recording may be found here: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S24796624>

This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with the built-in mic and R√∏de Rec application. This is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of this bird's utterances.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Perched in the bare limbs in the crown of  a deciduous tree. FOS this fall. 

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency **6 kHz**. 

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
